ty. This insight leads Bartlett to a consideration of the similarities and differences in the relationship of political philosophy and sophistry to pious faith. Bartlett’s superb exegesis offers a significant tool for understanding the history of philosophy, but, in tracing Socrates’s response to Protagoras’ teachings, Bartlett also builds toward a richer understanding of both ancient sophistry and what Socrates meant by “political philosophy.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aSophists (Greek philosophy) 0aSophists (Greek philosophy). 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aPlato.  aProtagoras.  aSocrates.  apolitical philosophy.  arelativism.  asophistry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226394312423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226394312/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles